04640nam a22005655i 9780822387978DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223879787 a10.1515/97808223879782doi  a(DE-B1597)553813  a(OCoLC)1224279654  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS480.45b.S563 2006 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a954.03/571 aSinha, Mrinalini, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpecters of Mother India :bThe Global Restructuring of an Empire /cMrinalini Sinha; Daniel J. Walkowitz. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRadical Perspectives00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbout the Series -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Nomenclature and Transliteration -- tIntroduction: The Anatomy of an Event -- t1. A Transitional Moment: The Dynamics of an Interwar Imperial Social Formation -- t2. Unpredictable Outcome: The Trajectory of a Transatlantic Intervention -- t3. Ironic Reversal: The Rhetoric of ''Facts'' in the Controversy over Mother India -- t4. Refashioning Mother India: The Sarda Act andWomen's Collective Agency -- t5. Ambiguous Aftermath: Political Consolidation on the Eve of the Second World War -- tEpilogue: History, Memory, Event -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpecters of Mother India tells the complex story of one episode that became the tipping point for an important historical transformation. The event at the center of the book is the massive international controversy that followed the 1927 publication of Mother India, an exposé written by the American journalist Katherine Mayo. Mother India provided graphic details of a variety of social ills in India, especially those related to the status of women and to the particular plight of the country's child wives. According to Mayo, the roots of the social problems she chronicled lay in an irredeemable Hindu culture that rendered India unfit for political self-government. Mother India was reprinted many times in the United States, Great Britain, and India; it was translated into more than a dozen languages; and it was reviewed in virtually every major publication on five continents.Sinha provides a rich historical narrative of the controversy surrounding Mother India, from the book's publication through the passage in India of the Child Marriage Restraint Act in the closing months of 1929. She traces the unexpected trajectory of the controversy as critics acknowledged many of the book's facts only to overturn its central premise. Where Mayo located blame for India's social backwardness within the beliefs and practices of Hinduism, the critics laid it at the feet of the colonial state, which they charged with impeding necessary social reforms. As Sinha shows, the controversy became a catalyst for some far-reaching changes, including a reconfiguration of the relationship between the political and social spheres in colonial India and the coalescence of a collective identity for women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aImperialismxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzIndiaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aWalkowitz, Daniel J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387978zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822387978.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-